"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Numbers chapter 3
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-numbers-3-3.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/numbers.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/numbers.json (MKT text)

Key Christological decisions in this range:
- Levite-for-firstborn substitution (vv12-13, 41-45) is the structural type of
  Christ's substitutionary work; the excess 273 firstborns redeemed with silver
  typifies Christ's ransom (1 Pet 1:18-19)
- Unauthorized approach = death (v10, v38) is the negative space that Heb 10:19-22
  inverts: Christ's blood opens the way into the holy place
- Kohath carries the ark (v31) — type of Christ bearing the full weight of divine presence
- Eleazar's succession (v32) points to the inadequacy of mortal priests and anticipates
  Heb 7:23-24 (Christ's permanent, non-transferable priesthood)
- "Give the Levites to Aaron" (v9) is typed by John 17:6 — Christ's people given by the Father
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NUMBERS = {
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>The chapter opens by naming the generation in which YHWH spoke to Moses at Sinai: &ldquo;the descendants of Aaron and Moses.&rdquo; That both the prophet (Moses) and the priest (Aaron) are named as the founding figures places ch 3 in the dual-office context of prophetic word and priestly intercession. Hebrews applies this dual-office framework to Christ alone, who is both the apostle (the one sent, the prophet) and the high priest of our confession (Heb 3:1). Numbers 3 inaugurates the priesthood that Hebrews will fully develop and surpass.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Aaron's four sons — Nadab, Abihu, Eleazar, Ithamar — are the Aaronic priestly line at its fullest extent. The mention of &ldquo;Nadab the firstborn&rdquo; anticipates the complication in v4: the firstborn priest died without taking over the high-priestly succession. The Aaronic priesthood is characterized from the beginning by discontinuity, death, and the need for succession — the very weakness that Hebrews identifies as the Aaronic order's fundamental inadequacy compared to Christ's eternal priesthood (Heb 7:23-24).</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;The anointed priests who were ordained to serve as priests&rdquo; — the word <em>anointed</em> (<em>meshuchim</em>) marks the Aaronic priests as set apart by oil, prefiguring the Anointed One (<em>Mashiach</em>, Messiah) whose anointing by the Spirit (Isa 61:1; Luke 4:18) is of an entirely different order. The priests were anointed for a role they could fulfill imperfectly and temporarily; Christ is anointed for a priesthood that is perfect and permanent. Their ordination to serve is the type; Christ's installation by divine oath (Heb 7:21: &ldquo;The Lord has sworn and will not change his mind, &lsquo;You are a priest forever&rsquo;&rdquo;) is the antitype.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;Nadab and Abihu died before the LORD when they offered unauthorized fire before the LORD in the wilderness of Sinai, and they had no sons.&rdquo; Two priests — the firstborn of the priestly line — died without heirs, severing the Nadab-Abihu branch. Their death before the LORD for unauthorized approach is the paradigmatic demonstration that sinful human beings cannot draw near to YHWH without proper mediation and authorization. Christ's priestly work is precisely the establishing of authorized access: &ldquo;Therefore, brothers, since we have confidence to enter the holy places by the blood of Jesus... let us draw near with a true heart&rdquo; (Heb 10:19-22). The death of Nadab and Abihu marks the price of unauthorized entry; Christ's blood marks the cost of authorized entry.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A divine-speech formula: YHWH speaks to Moses about the Levites. Every section of Numbers 3 that formally introduces the Levitical order begins with divine initiative — YHWH selects, appoints, assigns, and counts. The entire priestly-Levitical structure is YHWH's institution, not Israel's invention. Hebrews makes this point about Christ's priesthood as well: &ldquo;And no one takes this honor for himself, but only when called by God, just as Aaron was&rdquo; (Heb 5:4-5). Christ did not appoint himself high priest; he was appointed by the Father's eternal decree.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;Bring the tribe of Levi forward and present them to Aaron the priest, so they may serve him.&rdquo; YHWH gives people to Aaron as his servants — a gift that will be inverted and surpassed when Christ receives his people from the Father. In John 17:6, Jesus tells the Father: &ldquo;I have manifested your name to the people whom you gave me out of the world. Yours they were, and you gave them to me.&rdquo; The Levites given to Aaron by YHWH's command are the type of the church given to Christ by the Father's love. The priestly community is not self-assembled but divinely gifted.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Levites fulfill duties assigned to Aaron and &ldquo;the entire congregation&rdquo; — they serve vicariously, on behalf of the whole community of Israel. The concept of vicarious service is woven into the Levitical order from the beginning: the Levites bear what Israel cannot bear, serve where Israel cannot serve, approach what Israel cannot approach. This is the structural type of Christ's vicarious service: &ldquo;For even the Son of Man came not to be served but to serve, and to give his life as a ransom for many&rdquo; (Mark 10:45). Christ fulfills for his people what they cannot fulfill for themselves.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Levites are &ldquo;responsible for all the furnishings of the tent of meeting&rdquo; — they safeguard the holy instruments through which YHWH meets Israel. Paul develops this stewardship language for the apostolic ministry: &ldquo;This is how one should regard us, as servants of Christ and stewards of the mysteries of God&rdquo; (1 Cor 4:1). The new covenant community is the living temple (1 Cor 3:16), and its ministers are stewards of holy things — a continuation of the Levitical logic in a new key, now under Christ the high priest who is himself the temple (John 2:21).</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;Give the Levites to Aaron and his sons; they are wholly given to him from among the Israelites.&rdquo; The possessive giving of persons — the Levites are YHWH's gift to Aaron — is the type of Christ's gift of his people to the Father and the Father's gift of the redeemed to the Son. Jesus prays in John 17:9: &ldquo;I am praying for them. I am not praying for the world but for those whom you have given me, for they are yours.&rdquo; The logic of Numbers 3 — YHWH gives a people to the appointed priest for the priest's service — runs through the NT's account of election and priestly intercession.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;Appoint Aaron and his sons to serve; they shall maintain their priestly duties. Any unauthorized person (<em>zar</em>) who comes near shall be put to death.&rdquo; The <em>zar</em> (stranger, unauthorized person) who approaches the holy is executed — holiness requires authorized, mediated access. Christ's high-priestly work is the establishment of new authorization for the <em>zar</em>: &ldquo;Therefore, brothers, since we have confidence to enter the holy places by the blood of Jesus, by the new and living way that he opened for us through the curtain, that is, through his flesh... let us draw near&rdquo; (Heb 10:19-22). The unauthorized outsider is now authorized through Christ's sacrifice, the curtain-barrier abolished by his torn flesh.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A new divine speech: YHWH speaks about the Levite-for-firstborn exchange. The divine initiative is explicit: &ldquo;I have taken the Levites.&rdquo; YHWH acts first, establishing the substitution system before Israel can request or earn it. The pattern of divine initiative in the substitution — YHWH provides the substitute; Israel receives the benefit — prefigures the NT's account of atonement: &ldquo;God shows his love for us in that while we were still sinners, Christ died for us&rdquo; (Rom 5:8). The substitute is always YHWH's provision, not human achievement.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;I have taken the Levites from among the Israelites as substitutes (<em>tachat</em>) for every firstborn who opens the womb.&rdquo; <em>Tachat</em> (in place of, substituting for) is the OT's formal substitution term. The Levites stand in place of the firstborns — the firstborns are released from their obligation precisely because someone else takes it on. Christ's substitution employs the same logic at a deeper level: &ldquo;Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us&rdquo; (Gal 3:13). The Levites took the place of Israel's firstborns in service; Christ takes the place of all sinners under judgment. The structural principle of substitutionary representation is embedded in the Levitical order itself.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;For every firstborn is mine; when I struck down all the firstborn in Egypt, I set apart for myself all the firstborn in Israel.&rdquo; YHWH's claim on every firstborn, established at the Exodus judgment, is the basis for the entire Levitical substitution system. In the NT, this claim on the firstborn finds its ultimate expression in Christ, &ldquo;the firstborn of all creation&rdquo; (Col 1:15) and &ldquo;the firstborn from the dead&rdquo; (Col 1:18), who bears YHWH's claim on cosmic scope. The firstborn's consecration to YHWH — required since Egypt — is fulfilled when the eternal Son, the Father's firstborn, gives himself fully to the Father's purpose in the cross and resurrection.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Another divine-speech formula, this time initiating the Levite census by clan and family. The census of the tribe set apart for YHWH's service is divinely commanded — every person in the priestly-servant community is counted and accounted for. Christ's priestly knowledge of his own is expressed in John 10:3: &ldquo;he calls his own sheep by name.&rdquo; The shepherd-priest knows each individual in the flock; the census is the formal OT expression of this personal knowing and naming.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;Count every male from a month old and upward.&rdquo; The Levite census begins at one month — a lower threshold than the general census (twenty years) — because the Levites are not counted as soldiers but as substitutes for firstborns. Infants are included because even they represent YHWH's claim on human life. The counting from earliest life reflects the covenant's embrace of persons from birth, foreshadowing the NT's affirmation that covenant membership is not earned by years but received — &ldquo;for to such belongs the kingdom of heaven&rdquo; (Matt 19:14).</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;Moses counted them just as the LORD had directed.&rdquo; Moses's faithful execution of the census command is the pattern of obedient service: he does not modify, skip, or reinterpret the divine instruction. Hebrews uses Moses's faithfulness as the foil for Christ's greater faithfulness: &ldquo;Moses was faithful in all God's house as a servant... but Christ is faithful over God's house as a son&rdquo; (Heb 3:5-6). Every act of Moses's obedience is the type of Christ's obedience; Christ fulfills the faithfulness that Moses modeled but as the Son rather than the servant.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The three sons of Levi — Gershon, Kohath, and Merari — are the founders of the three Levitical clan-divisions. Their three roles in tabernacle service (fabric/covering, sacred objects, structural framing) represent three dimensions of the sanctuary's existence: the outer covering that protects it, the inner holy objects that constitute its purpose, and the structural frame that gives it form. Christ is simultaneously the covering of his people (their righteousness), the sacred object at the center of the new temple (the incarnate Presence), and the cornerstone that gives the community its structural form (Eph 2:20-22).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The Gershonite sub-clans: Libni and Shimei. The Gershonites carry the fabric components of the tabernacle — curtains, coverings, and screens (ch 4). Their work involves the tabernacle's outer layer, the boundary between the holy space and the world. The church as Christ's body forms a similar boundary: it is the presence of the holy among the profane, the visible community that makes the invisible God accessible (Matt 5:14: &ldquo;you are the light of the world&rdquo;).</p>",
    "19": "<p>The Kohathite sub-clans: Amram, Izhar, Hebron, and Uzziel. The Kohathites carry the most sacred objects — including the ark (ch 4). Amram is Moses and Aaron's father; the founding priestly family descends from the Kohathite clan designated to bear the holiest things. The Kohathite mission — to carry YHWH's presence in the ark — is the type of every bearer of the divine word and sacrament. Christ is the ultimate Kohathite: the one who bears the full presence of God not on poles on his shoulders but in his own person (Col 2:9).</p>",
    "20": "<p>The Merarite sub-clans: Mahli and Mushi. The Merarites carry the tabernacle's structural components — the frames, bars, pillars, and bases (ch 4). Their service is the least visible but foundationally necessary: without the structural skeleton, the fabrics and holy objects have nowhere to dwell. Christ is described as the foundation of the community that houses his presence: &ldquo;No one can lay a foundation other than that which is laid, which is Jesus Christ&rdquo; (1 Cor 3:11). The Merarite structural service typifies the foundational, load-bearing work of Christ that enables everything else.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Gershonite clans by name: Libni and Shimei. Both clans trace back to Levi's firstborn son, making Gershon the founding line even though the Kohathites carry the holiest objects. Gershon's priority of birth versus Kohath's priority of sacred assignment reflects a pattern in Scripture: natural primogeniture is regularly superseded by divine calling. Christ comes not from Levi at all (Heb 7:14: &ldquo;It is evident that our Lord was descended from Judah&rdquo;), which is why Hebrews argues that his priesthood is of a different and greater order than the entire Levitical system.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Gershon's total: 7,500 males from a month old and upward — smaller than Kohath (8,600) despite Gershon's firstborn status. In the Levitical census the largest clan carries the holiest objects, not the firstborn clan — a consistent biblical inversion of birth-order privilege. The greatest servant is not the one with the highest natural status but the one given the most sacred commission. Christ inverts the world's hierarchy of greatness: &ldquo;whoever would be great among you must be your servant&rdquo; (Matt 20:26).</p>",
    "23": "<p>The Gershonites camp behind the tabernacle, on the west side — the rearmost clan, behind the holy of holies. The arrangement of the Levitical clans creates a layered defense: priests are closest (east), then Kohathites (south), Gershonites (west), and Merarites (north). The most sacred approach is from the east, toward the sunrise; the most distal position is the west. Christ as the &ldquo;sun of righteousness&rdquo; (Mal 4:2) rises from the east — the direction of the tabernacle's entrance and of his priestly approach.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Eliasaph son of Lael is the head of the Gershonite ancestral house. Both names are theophoric — a small indication that the Levitical families maintained an awareness of their divine calling even in personal names. The names of those entrusted with holy service reflect their purpose. Christ's own name carries its commission: &ldquo;you shall call his name Jesus, for he will save his people from their sins&rdquo; (Matt 1:21).</p>",
    "25": "<p>The Gershonites are responsible for the tabernacle's fabric: the tabernacle itself, the tent with its covering, and the screen at the entrance. The word <em>ohel</em> (tent) and <em>mishkan</em> (tabernacle/dwelling) both appear — the distinction is between the innermost fabric structure and the outer tent coverings. Christ is the one who &ldquo;dwelt (<em>eskēnōsen</em>, tabernacled) among us&rdquo; (John 1:14) — his incarnation is the <em>mishkan</em> made flesh, the divine dwelling-fabric stretched over human form.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The Gershonites also care for the courtyard curtains and entrance screen. The courtyard screen is the first boundary between the profane world and the holy space — the outer gate that admits or excludes. Christ calls himself the gate of the sheepfold (John 10:9: &ldquo;I am the door; if anyone enters by me, he will be saved&rdquo;). The Gershonite care of the courtyard entrance screen is the type of Christ's role as the gateway through which the profane world may legitimately enter the presence of God.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The Kohathite clans: Amram, Izhar, Hebron, and Uzziel — four clans from Kohath's four sons. The Amramites include Moses and Aaron's family; the Uzzielites include those who carried Nadab and Abihu's bodies after the judgment of Lev 10. The Kohathite clan encompasses both the founding priestly family (Amram → Aaron → the high priesthood) and the service clergy who assist the priests. Christ is both — the high priest par excellence and the servant of all (Mark 10:45).</p>",
    "28": "<p>Kohath's total: 8,600 males — the largest of the three Levitical clans. The largest clan carries the holiest objects: ark, table, lampstand, altars. Size and sacred commission are correlated in an inverse world where the most sacred task is the most dangerous (Num 4:15, 20: approaching the holy objects without authorization means death). Christ as the one who bears the fullness of divine presence in his own body (Col 1:19) bears the weight no other person can bear — the entire gravity of divine presence resting in a single human frame.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The Kohathites camp on the south side of the tabernacle — the most proximate non-eastern position. Their camping location reflects their sacred carrying responsibility: stationed nearest to the holy objects they transport. Those who bear the most sacred things live closest to the danger. Christ's proximity to the Father (John 1:18: &ldquo;No one has ever seen God; the only God, who is at the Father's side, has made him known&rdquo;) is the ultimate expression of this proximity-principle: the bearer of the full divine presence dwells in the Father's own bosom.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Elizaphan son of Uzziel is the head of the Kohathites — a nephew of Aaron (Uzziel was Aaron's uncle) who supervises the clan that includes Aaron's family. The distinction between the priestly clan (Aaron's sons) and the Levitical supervisory clan (Elizaphan) preserves the hierarchy: Levites serve under priests; even the most senior Levite chief does not displace the priestly order. Christ embodies both offices without hierarchy — he is simultaneously the priest and the one who directs the priestly community.</p>",
    "31": "<p>&ldquo;They shall be responsible for the ark, the table, the lampstand, the altars, the vessels of the sanctuary used in the holy service, and the screen.&rdquo; The Kohathites carry the ark of the covenant — YHWH's throne-seat — along with the sacred furniture of the holy place. The <em>kapporeth</em> (mercy seat) on the ark's lid is the place of atonement where the high priest sprinkles blood on Yom Kippur (Lev 16:14-15). The Kohathites carry the atonement-seat; Christ is the atonement itself: &ldquo;God put forward [Christ] as a propitiation (<em>hilastērion</em>, the same Greek word as the LXX for <em>kapporeth</em>) by his blood&rdquo; (Rom 3:25). The ark-bearers carry the type; Christ is the substance.</p>",
    "32": "<p>&ldquo;Eleazar son of Aaron the priest shall be chief over the leaders of the Levites, with oversight of those who keep watch over the sanctuary.&rdquo; Eleazar is appointed priestly overseer of all Levitical service — a role he will inherit fully when Aaron dies (Num 20:28). The continual need to appoint successors demonstrates the Aaronic priesthood's mortality-problem. Hebrews uses this exact pattern: &ldquo;The former priests were many in number, because they were prevented by death from continuing in office, but he [Christ] holds his priesthood permanently, because he continues forever&rdquo; (Heb 7:23-24). Eleazar succeeds Aaron; but no one succeeds Christ — his is the priesthood that does not pass to another.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The Merarite clans: Mahli and Mushi — Merari's two sons. The Merarites carry the structural skeleton of the tabernacle: the frames, bars, pillars, and bases — the hardware that gives the holy space its physical form. Without Merari's cargo, there is no structure into which the Gershonites' fabrics can hang or within which the Kohathites' holy objects can reside. The foundational, structural, and unglamorous work makes the beautiful and holy possible. Paul applies this foundation-logic to Christ: &ldquo;no one can lay a foundation other than that which is laid, which is Jesus Christ&rdquo; (1 Cor 3:11).</p>",
    "34": "<p>Merari's total: 6,200 — the smallest Levitical clan. The clan that carries the heaviest physical cargo (bronze and wood structural components) is the smallest in number. The paradox of small numbers bearing the heaviest loads echoes throughout Scripture: Gideon's 300, David against Goliath, the twelve disciples sent to the world. Christ's &ldquo;foolishness of God&rdquo; and &ldquo;weakness of God&rdquo; (1 Cor 1:25) are stronger than all human strength — the small, despised things of the world bearing what the great cannot.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Zuriel son of Abihail is the head of the Merarites; they camp on the north side of the tabernacle. The north position in Hebrew cosmology is associated with the &ldquo;far north&rdquo; as the seat of divine assembly (cf. Ps 48:2; Isa 14:13: &ldquo;I will sit on the mount of assembly in the far reaches of the north&rdquo;). The Merarites camping on the north maintain the structure at the furthest point from the priestly entrance — framing the boundary between the holy assembly and the outer reaches of the creation.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The Merarites are responsible for the tabernacle's structural hardware: frames (<em>qerashim</em>), crossbars (<em>berichim</em>), pillars (<em>ammudim</em>), and sockets (<em>adonim</em>). These are the backbone components — the structural theology of the covenant dwelling translated into bronze and acacia wood. Christ is described as the cornerstone of the new temple (Eph 2:20: &ldquo;built on the foundation of the apostles and prophets, Christ Jesus himself being the cornerstone&rdquo;) — the structural element around which the entire community is aligned.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The Merarites also care for the outer courtyard pillars with their sockets, pegs, and ropes. The pegs and ropes that anchor the tabernacle to the ground are the humblest of all sacred components — yet without them the structure collapses. The ministry of tent-pegging is not visible in the finished tabernacle but essential to its stability. Christ's hidden, pre-incarnate work of holding all things together (Col 1:17: &ldquo;in him all things hold together&rdquo;) is the cosmic equivalent of the Merarite pegs — invisible but foundational.</p>",
    "38": "<p>&ldquo;Moses, Aaron, and his sons shall camp in front of the tabernacle, on the east side toward the sunrise. They are responsible for the sanctuary as a duty on behalf of Israel; and any unauthorized person who approaches shall be put to death.&rdquo; The priests camp at the sunrise side — the place of beginning and approach. Christ's priestly station is at the Father's right hand, the place of intercession and access. His is the only approach that does not incur death; all authorized approach to the Father now passes through him (John 14:6: &ldquo;no one comes to the Father except through me&rdquo;). He took the position of the unauthorized one (bearing death on the cross) so that others may approach as authorized.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The grand total of Levites: 22,000 males from a month old and upward. The 22,000 Levites serve as substitutes for the 22,273 firstborn Israelites (v43), with 273 left over who require monetary redemption. The near-match between the two populations displays the precision of YHWH's substitution system — the Levites' number was calibrated against the firstborn census. The slight shortfall (273) is not accidental; it is the built-in demonstration that the Levitical substitution, though comprehensive, is not perfectly sufficient — pointing to the one who is.</p>",
    "40": "<p>YHWH commands the counting of every firstborn male in Israel from a month old and upward, with a record of their names. The command to record the firstborns &ldquo;by name&rdquo; is significant: each firstborn is a person with a name, not merely a statistical unit. Christ, the true firstborn, knows each of his people by name (John 10:3: &ldquo;he calls his own sheep by name and leads them out&rdquo;). The firstborn census counting names is the type of the good shepherd's personal knowledge of his flock.</p>",
    "41": "<p>&ldquo;Take the Levites for me — I am the LORD — in place of all the firstborn Israelites, and the Levites' livestock in place of their livestock.&rdquo; YHWH ratifies the exchange. The formula &ldquo;I am YHWH&rdquo; (<em>ani YHWH</em>) attached to this command marks the substitution as a divine act — YHWH himself authorizes the exchange. In the NT, God himself provides the substitute: &ldquo;God so loved the world, that he gave his only Son&rdquo; (John 3:16). The divine initiative in substitution — YHWH provides what YHWH requires — is the deep structure of both the Levitical exchange and the cross.</p>",
    "42": "<p>Moses obeys the census command for the firstborns. The consistent execution of divine commands — census, substitution, redemption — builds the administrative framework that embodies the theological truth of vicarious representation. Every step in the substitution process is carried out in obedience: Moses counts, Aaron receives, YHWH accepts. Christ's execution of the Father's redemptive plan follows the same obedience-pattern: &ldquo;he humbled himself by becoming obedient to the point of death, even death on a cross&rdquo; (Phil 2:8).</p>",
    "43": "<p>The firstborn count: 22,273. The precision of this number — slightly more than 22,000 Levites — creates the &ldquo;remainder problem&rdquo; that drives vv46-51. The census reveals that the substitution is not quite sufficient: 273 firstborns exceed the Levite supply. YHWH's substitution system is comprehensive but not perfectly proportional — there is always a remainder the system cannot cover. This is the structural argument of Hebrews: the Levitical system could not make perfect those who drew near (Heb 10:1). The 273 excess firstborns are the textual emblem of the system's insufficiency, requiring a supplementary ransom.</p>",
    "44": "<p>YHWH speaks again to authorize the monetary redemption of the 273 excess firstborns. The divine-speech formula marks each element of the substitution transaction as commanded, not improvised. The gap between the Levite supply and the firstborn demand is not a failure of the system but a feature: it reveals the system's limits and points toward a more comprehensive solution. Hebrews argues precisely this: the Levitical system &ldquo;can never, by the same sacrifices that are continually offered every year, make perfect those who draw near&rdquo; (Heb 10:1).</p>",
    "45": "<p>&ldquo;Take the Levites in place of all the firstborn Israelites, and the Levites' livestock in place of their livestock.&rdquo; The main exchange — 22,000 Levites covering 22,000 firstborns — is ratified and complete. The remaining 273 are the subject of vv46-51. The completeness of the main exchange and the incompleteness for the 273 remainder together form the typological argument: Christ's single sacrifice is the complete substitution that the Levitical partial-substitution pointed toward. He is the substitute who covers not most but all — &ldquo;the Lamb of God, who takes away the sin of the world&rdquo; (John 1:29).</p>",
    "46": "<p>&ldquo;For the redemption of the two hundred and seventy-three firstborn Israelites who exceed the number of Levites, you shall collect five shekels per person.&rdquo; The 273 who fall outside the Levite-for-firstborn substitution are redeemed with silver — a monetary ransom. The principle is clear: where the substitute system cannot cover, a price must be paid. This remnant-redemption by silver is the type of Christ's ransom: &ldquo;you were ransomed from the futile ways inherited from your forefathers, not with perishable things such as silver or gold, but with the precious blood of Christ&rdquo; (1 Pet 1:18-19). The five-shekel silver ransom is surpassed by the infinitely greater ransom of Christ's blood.</p>",
    "47": "<p>&ldquo;You shall collect five shekels per person, reckoned in the sanctuary shekel — the shekel being twenty gerahs.&rdquo; The sanctuary shekel is the standard for cultic transactions — a fixed, divine-authority weight that cannot be manipulated. The precision of the redemption price reflects YHWH's exact accounting of covenant obligations. In the NT, the ransom is also precisely accounted: Christ's sacrifice satisfies the exact righteous requirement of the law (Rom 8:3-4: &ldquo;God... condemned sin in the flesh, in order that the righteous requirement of the law might be fulfilled in us&rdquo;). No surplus, no shortfall — the ransom is exact.</p>",
    "48": "<p>&ldquo;Give the redemption money to Aaron and his sons.&rdquo; The monetary redemption for the 273 flows to the priestly family — supporting the priests who bear the service of the sanctuary. In the NT, the redemption accomplished by Christ does not flow to a human priestly family but creates a royal priesthood from the redeemed themselves: &ldquo;you are a chosen race, a royal priesthood, a holy nation, a people for his own possession&rdquo; (1 Pet 2:9). The redeemed become priests — a transformation the five-shekel silver transaction could only faintly suggest.</p>",
    "49": "<p>Moses collects the redemption money from the excess firstborns. The administrative precision — person-by-person collection from those who cannot be covered by the Levite exchange — illustrates that YHWH's covenant accounting is thorough. No one falls through a gap unnoticed; every uncovered person is individually accounted for and redeemed. Christ's priestly intercession maintains the same comprehensive coverage: &ldquo;he is able to save to the uttermost those who draw near to God through him, since he always lives to make intercession for them&rdquo; (Heb 7:25).</p>",
    "50": "<p>The total redemption money: 1,365 shekels in the sanctuary weight (273 × 5 = 1,365). The arithmetic is exact and transparent — the reader can verify the calculation. YHWH's covenant transactions are not opaque; they are conducted openly, with full disclosure. The transparency of the redemption price anticipates the gospel's open proclamation of what the atonement cost: &ldquo;We preach Christ crucified&rdquo; (1 Cor 1:23). The price is displayed publicly — not hidden but declared.</p>",
    "51": "<p>&ldquo;Moses gave the redemption money to Aaron and his sons, just as the LORD had commanded.&rdquo; The chapter closes with the compliance formula — the entire Levitical substitution and firstborn redemption transaction has been executed exactly as commanded. The completeness of Moses's obedience anticipates the completeness of Christ's obedience: &ldquo;It is finished&rdquo; (John 19:30). The Levitical substitution system is fully implemented in Num 3; the new covenant substitution is fully accomplished at Calvary. Both end with the same note: every divine requirement has been met, every debt accounted for, every person redeemed or covered. Numbers 3 is the shadow; the cross is the substance.</p>"
  }
}

